rashid sumaila the leopold leadership program skip to main content search this site the leopold leadership program about fellows news fellowship information resources fellows login home 2013 fellowship information all cohort reunion june 19 21 2012 in this section fellows directory one of the best things i have ever done in my career it changed my views of how to do my job alan townsend 2001 rashid sumaila rashid sumaila contact information how can we integrate economics with ecology and other disciplines to help ensure the sustainability of our fisheries resources for the benefit of current and future generations sumaila addresses issues such as i economics of fish stock rebuilding ii trade and coral reefs sustainability iii climate change and fisheries and iv fisheries subsidies and fish sustainability what's new the fisheries economics research unit has been working hard to prepare a chapter for the upcoming green economy report which is part of the united nations environment programme's unep green economy initiative and recently the star of the ellen degeneres show has plugged the documentary film end of line in which dr sumaila is featured proessor & director fisheries centre university of british columbia peak fish has already been reached world marine fish catch has been declining since the late 1980s overfishing is nearly ubiquitous at this point the question isn t whether the world's fisheries are sustainable it's whether they can ever be sustainable searching for an answer conservationists worried over the health of the oceans have often found themselves pitted against fishers concerned for their livelihoods but is this conflict necessary dr ussif rashid sumaila tries to balance economic and ecological realities in order to create fisheries that are both responsible and profitable as a global fisheries economist sumaila uses economic tools to analyze marine reserves illegal fishing trends government subsidies and other knotty issues that make up the overall picture of global fisheries economics though global fisheries are geographically far apart they are ecologically and socioeconomically connected for example the state of fish populations in west africa may have repercussions in europe both by altering interwoven ecosystems and by sparking emigration the upshot is that we all every one of us need to find feasible ways of stepping back from the overfishing precipice tags ecology economics fisheries economics north america ocean sustainability and conservation 2012 leopold leadership program the stanford woods institute for the environment stanford university stanford ca 94305
